{
  "answer": "**Manu on *danda* (the rod of punishment/coercion) as divinely instituted:**\n\nThe strongest passage frames *danda* explicitly as created by the Lord at the beginning of time: \"For his sake, the Lord in the beginning created `Daṇḍa`, his own son, as Dharma, the protector of all beings, formed of the spiritual luster of Brahma.\"[^1] Supporting verses emphasize its divine necessity: all beings submit through fear of it; the king embodies it as protector; and *danda* itself is equated with Dharma.[^2]\n\n**Charles Comte in *Traité de Législation*, Vol. II, on state coercion:**\n\nNo passages in the English translation of Vol. II (chapters on human physical/intellectual development across peoples/climates) directly frame state coercion as a \"conditioned product of historical violence.\" Searches across Comte's works for terms like \"coercion,\" \"violence,\" \"force,\" \"state,\" \"government,\" \"origin,\" and combinations yielded no matching lines on this topic. If present in the French original or another volume (e.g., Vol. I on legislative theory or *Propriété* on property/state origins), it does not appear in the translated corpus.\n\n**Durability across regime change:**\n\nManu's divine framing—*danda* as an eternal, God-created essence underlying order—proves more durable. It transcends specific rulers or histories, binding legitimacy to cosmic Dharma regardless of who wields the rod.[^3] A historical/conditioned view (if Comte articulated one) ties coercion to contingent violence, vulnerable to new regimes reinterpreting origins to delegitimize predecessors.\n\n[^1]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 7, ¶p-73f910](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-73f910).\n\n[^2]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 7](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-55e886).\n\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 7](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/).",
